Chapter 1
Cohren
4:30 AM, Itania time. Cohren hated waking up that early. Especially since it was his responsibility to wake up the rest of his company's members. He quietly got out of his bunk, put on his combat uniform, strapped on his tactical vest, and gathered the items from his locker, paying particular attention to a small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and clipped his helmet to a small hook attached to his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: respirator, goggles, everything. After checking his ammo pouches, he calmly exited the barracks, the sound of crushed mud and ice echoing beneath his boots.
He pulled out a lighter from his tactical vest pocket and a cigarette from the other. Lighting it, he took a small drag before opening the door slowly. The previous week, he had had to be creative to wake up the men and women under his command. He had stopped using the pre-set alarm clock, half the time it didn't work, as anything that came out of the speakers was just a faint whistle.
"Do you wake them up?" Cohren turned to see Second Lieutenant Nemic walking towards him.
"Do you?"
"Do you plan on using something different this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and other soldiers rushed out, already dressed and equipped.
"Hello," said Craith.
"What woke you up?", Cohren asked.
"Well, primo, we didn't want to see what you had planned to wake us up today. Secundo, the first shock troops up are the first at breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be."
"You scored one, Specialist," said Cohren. He extended his hand and flipped a switch. A loud and screaming alarm blared inside the barracks, and he heard commotion and agitation from within.
"Good grief, Valturi", Nemic exclaimed. "We would have thought they would have learned to wake up at the same time as you by now."
"Well, my training camp buddies here did it," Cohren turned to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "But, once again, their squad and section leaders know how to wake up before their units."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company poured out in a rush. They all had what they needed, from personal belongings to necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits looked disoriented, while others seemed annoyed.
"Hello everyone," said Cohren cheerfully.
"Excuse me, sir, why are you insisting on waking us up this way?", asked one of the shock troop members, a corporal.
"Because standard wake-ups are crap. And because Daybreak doesn't sleep in."
"Make sure you have all your personal gear," he continued. As first lieutenant and commander's assistant, it was his responsibility to oversee and assist the company with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We're not returning. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I give you and your units fifty minutes to conduct final checks and retrieve rations for the day."
Members of the Exodus Company dispersed. They were part of the Second Shock Troop Division, Second Army. Initially, they were separated into two distinct companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being reunited. It was a scattered company, and Cohren was unsure what to make of his promotion to first lieutenant, mainly the reasons that had motivated it.
Cohren and Nemic, the first platoon's section leader, walked together under the light of numerous base-operational-advance illuminations, powered by generators. Most were tinted red to conceal them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild Weasel assaults, both aerial and ground, to counter them.
"New day, new mission for the pioneers of hell," Nemic began with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"An advanced operational base outside of Ianlos. We've been sent to support the ground assault," Cohren replied, pulling on his cigarette. A part of him blamed Craith for getting him started on smoking, but a year of combat had changed a man, and he remained silent.
"Shit. The situation is deteriorating on the front," Nemic muttered. "All the news coming from this place is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send aid to the Kurgan front.' Why not send aid to the Howland front?"
"Alright, brother," said Cohren, flicking his butt into the mud. "We're moving out with the first armored platoon, so we won't have to walk. Captain Shaw should be here."
"Shaw sent us a transport?", Nemic asked, a bit surprised.
"Honestly, it's not as bad as I thought. I mean, it's not exceptional, but it's not unbearable."
Cohren raised his pinky and index fingers to his throat mic while adjusting his backpack. "All units of Exodus Company, report to the west vehicle park when you're done. We're moving out with the first armored platoon at 0500."
Every few seconds, he received responses from the squadron leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were all low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they got here. All four had been very close friends since their initial training on Earth. It seemed like a lifetime ago, even though it couldn't have been more than two years. They were squadron leaders back then. But Craith was now commanding the second platoon since last week, after the previous commander was demobilized, wounded by a Daybreak sniper.
As they walked towards the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic saw a group of approximately eight main battle tanks Kronos and four Strykers. Their crews were busy, making sure their war machines were ready to depart. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking with the commander of the armored platoon. As they approached, Shaw turned and walked towards them, his normally cold face reflecting no emotion.
"Second Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's pistol holster before looking at them again. "I suppose the company is ready."
